qas.question: Which two languages does Dutch most closely resemble?
Which Germanic accent mark do both the English and the Dutch language not use?
Unlike English, both German and Dutch use how many genders in their grammar?
Which verb tense have both English and Dutch mostly gotten rid of?
Does Dutch borrow more or less from Romance languages for its vocabulary than German?

context: Dutch is one of the closest relatives of both <a0_0>German and English<a0_0/>[n 5] and is said to be roughly in between them.[n 6] Dutch, like English, has not undergone the High German consonant shift, does not use Germanic <a1_0>umlaut<a1_0/> as a grammatical marker, has largely abandoned the use of the <a3_0>subjunctive<a3_0/>, and has levelled much of its morphology, including the case system.[n 7] Features shared with German include the survival of <a2_0>three<a2_0/> grammatical genders—albeit with few grammatical consequences[n 8]—as well as the use of modal particles, final-obstruent devoicing, and a similar word order.[n 9] Dutch vocabulary is mostly Germanic and incorporates <a4_0>more<a4_0/> Romance loans than German but fewer than English.[n 10]
